WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.334 --> 00:00:01.750
CARRIE LAURENO:
Welcome to Google,

00:00:01.750 --> 00:00:04.350
for those of us who
are visiting today.

00:00:04.350 --> 00:00:05.500
My name is Carrie Laurena.

00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:07.560
I am the founder of the
Google Veterans Network

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:10.940
and head up our veteran
outreach strategy here.

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:14.139
Happy early Veterans Day
to everyone in the room.

00:00:14.139 --> 00:00:15.680
I feel like we're
among family today.

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:19.950
I see so many familiar faces,
both people who work here

00:00:19.950 --> 00:00:23.150
at Google, many of our
non-profit partners,

00:00:23.150 --> 00:00:25.460
distinguished guests
from the military.

00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:27.630
Thank you all for
being here today

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:31.650
in celebration of Veterans
Day and to help us here

00:00:31.650 --> 00:00:33.630
at Google celebrate
the way we wanted to,

00:00:33.630 --> 00:00:36.170
which is working towards
our goal of bridging

00:00:36.170 --> 00:00:39.500
the civil military divide.

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:41.470
The reason that
we're here today is

00:00:41.470 --> 00:00:44.000
to celebrate an exhibit
that opened on Friday

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.320
at the 9/11 Memorial Museum that
is called The Call to Serve,

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:52.120
recognizing the extraordinary
service of our military

00:00:52.120 --> 00:00:55.050
in the immediate wake
of the 9/11 attacks.

00:00:55.050 --> 00:00:58.240
After over a decade
of war and, everything

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:03.030
that happened in Iraq, the
immediate accomplishments

00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:05.340
of our military, frankly,
were overshadowed,

00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:07.320
and there were so
many early successes

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:10.477
that are not brought
to the light of day.

00:01:10.477 --> 00:01:12.560
And we wanted to help bring
those stories to life,

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:15.430
and to recognize
those individuals who

00:01:15.430 --> 00:01:19.720
made really truly extraordinary
achievements and contributions

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:23.710
on behalf of all of us
who have not served.

00:01:23.710 --> 00:01:26.140
We were fortunate
enough to brainstorm

00:01:26.140 --> 00:01:30.000
about this idea with Michael
Frazier, our friend and partner

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:31.820
at the 9/11 Museum,
the Executive Vice

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:34.372
President of Communications
and Marketing.

00:01:34.372 --> 00:01:35.330
Where are you, Michael?

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:40.450
In the back, of course.

00:01:40.450 --> 00:01:43.000
So Michael I had a conversation
a couple months ago.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.090
And we said, this is this
incredibly beautiful museum

00:01:47.090 --> 00:01:48.730
that had just opened in May.

00:01:48.730 --> 00:01:51.310
What could we do in
advance of Veterans Day

00:01:51.310 --> 00:01:54.580
to support the 9/11
Museum in their mission

00:01:54.580 --> 00:01:59.050
to recognize the overwhelming
number of acts of compassion

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:01.720
in the wake of 9/11, which
is part of their mission?

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:04.240
And we happen to have
some technology that

00:02:04.240 --> 00:02:05.919
helps people tell stories.

00:02:05.919 --> 00:02:06.960
We launched it last year.

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:09.610
It's called Google Tour
Builder, and it enables anyone

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:11.480
out there, any
aspiring storyteller,

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:15.520
to drop a pin on a map,
add a little bit of copy

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:18.237
to that, up to 25 photos
and videos in one place,

00:02:18.237 --> 00:02:20.570
pull it all together in a
beautiful storytelling format.

00:02:20.570 --> 00:02:23.950
And I like to joke that we built
this so that my mom could do it

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:25.910
without any assistance
for me whatsoever.

00:02:25.910 --> 00:02:28.690
It's really that easy
for any storyteller

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:32.250
to go in and talk
about their journey.

00:02:32.250 --> 00:02:35.695
And who has better stories
to tell than the military?

00:02:35.695 --> 00:02:38.900
The most incredible
achievements in the most amazing

00:02:38.900 --> 00:02:41.920
far off places that most of us
never have a chance to visit.

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:44.410
And what if we
could work together,

00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:47.430
the 9/11 Museum and Google, to
bring those stories to life,

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:49.740
to bring them to museum,
and to bring them

00:02:49.740 --> 00:02:52.390
into the public
eye at a time when

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:55.030
the public is tiring of the war.

00:02:55.030 --> 00:02:57.330
And there are a lot
of other stories

00:02:57.330 --> 00:03:00.630
that are out there
about service members.

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:05.200
What if we can convince-- coerce
in the most positive way--

00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:08.180
some of our most humble service
members, who truly have done

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:12.130
amazing things, to share their
stories in a way that might

00:03:12.130 --> 00:03:16.600
inspire other service
members to do the same.

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:19.781
I've learned an important
lesson from a friend and partner

00:03:19.781 --> 00:03:20.280
of ours.

00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:24.180
Colonel Jim Eisenhower, who is
at the Joint Chiefs of Staff

00:03:24.180 --> 00:03:28.050
and runs the reintegration
office for that team,

00:03:28.050 --> 00:03:30.480
has taught me a lesson
that service members

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:32.020
return to communities.

00:03:32.020 --> 00:03:33.980
And we want communities
to be a place that

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:38.250
are welcoming to our service
members and their families

00:03:38.250 --> 00:03:41.710
so that as they face
those difficult chapters

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:43.850
of transition that
are ahead of them,

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:45.850
that there's greater
awareness and understanding

00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:49.700
about those issues, and
that service members feel

00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:51.670
good about going
home and are embraced

00:03:51.670 --> 00:03:53.830
by the people who
do care about them

00:03:53.830 --> 00:03:55.970
the most in very
practical, tangible ways.

00:03:55.970 --> 00:03:58.639
So we're going to talk a little
bit about all that today.

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:00.930
We're going to share with
you some of the exhibit here,

00:04:00.930 --> 00:04:02.810
encourage all of you
go down to the museum

00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:06.025
this week during Veterans
Week to see it before Friday.

00:04:06.025 --> 00:04:07.650
And if you haven't
been able to see it,

00:04:07.650 --> 00:04:13.370
you can check it out online at
911memorial.org/calltoserve.

00:04:13.370 --> 00:04:15.970
That will be there
in perpetuity,

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:18.429
and a wonderful tribute
to the gentlemen

00:04:18.429 --> 00:04:20.220
that you're going to
meet in a few minutes.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:24.140
So without further ado, I'd
like to invite all of our guests

00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:27.460
onstage to join us.

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:29.590
Ladies and gentlemen, please
meet your storytellers

00:04:29.590 --> 00:04:31.867
and these incredible
service members.

